  "dateModified": "2025-10-11",
  "datePublished": "2025-10-11",
  "description": "¶Abstract In RLHF, a model adapts to a fixed feedback distribution. This is the asymmetric stability setting of Information-Theoretic Stability as Reward Function: the model\u0026rsquo;s stability reward is a function of its coupling to the feedback source, not an intrinsic property. We show that RLHF training dynamics instantiate the two-channel decomposition — alignment progress equals behavioral convergence plus responsiveness increase — and that the MI-dominates-marginal inequality gives a structural constraint on training: the model\u0026rsquo;s responsiveness to feedback can never be doing worse than its behavioral convergence. These results reframe alignment as an informational accounting problem rather than a moral one.\n",
